path, the real meaning of dharma is &quot;duty, that which is cor=\r\nrect&quot;. We\nhave a sense of responsibility towards so many entities, stemming=\r\n from\nour conditioning (vasana). This includes a sense of responsibility\nto=\r\nwards body, name, wife, children, parents, relatives, community,\ncountry, r=\r\neligion, subjects of study (e.g. Jyotish) etc etc. Every sense\nof &quot;I need t=\r\no do this&quot;, whether noble or evil, comes from one&#39;s\nconditioning and *binds=\r\n* one. If one surrenders all these, i.e.\neffectively one surrenders one&#39;s e=\r\nntire conditioning, at Lord&#39;s feet and\naccepts whatever happens to one as g=\r\nod&#39;s prasad, then one is liberated.\n&gt; =C2\n&gt; Based on the &quot;momentum&quot; from ac=\r\ntions before liberation, one may face\nvarious life situations even after li=\r\nberation. In one case, one may get\ncancer and die. In another case, one may=\r\n roam the world and spread\nSanatana Dharma. In another case, one may sit in=\r\n a cave and meditate for\n10,000 more years. In another case, one may roam t=\r\nhe streets looking\nlike a mad person. In another case, one may continue to =\r\nwork as a day\nlabourer. In another case, one may destroy a kingdom in a bat=\r\ntle. And so\non. In all these cases, the liberated being has surrendered all=\r\n\npreferences, all likes and dislikes, all agendas, attachments and sense\nof=\r\n resposibility towards everything one has (body, name, wife, children\netc a=\r\nnd all attributes of the body-mind complex that once ruled the\nroost) and e=\r\nngages in spontaneous actions based on the circumstances one\nfinds oneself =\r\nin, based on pre-existing momentum. Nothing that happens\nto one binds one a=\r\nnd nothing that one does binds one.\n&gt; =C2\n&gt; Liberation does not mean that a=\r\nll of one&#39;s belongings (body, name,\nfamily, community etc) are &quot;safe&quot; and &quot;=\r\nwell&quot;. Nor does it mean that one\ndoes nothing. Things may keep happening to=\r\n one and one may keep doing\nthings. Yet, one is untouched by them, like a w=\r\nater drop on a lotus\nleaf, because one has no desires, demands, preferences=\r\n or agendas and\naccepts whatever Lord gives.\n&gt; =C2\n&gt; *=C2 =C2 =C2 =C2 =C2 =\r\n=C2 =C2  *=C2 =C2 =C2 =C2 =C2 =C2\n=C2  *\n&gt; =C2\n&gt; One who tells Krishna, &quot;I =\r\nsurrender to you. I will not follow any\nreligion or rituals or gods and jus=\r\nt pray to you. So forgive all my sins\nand make sure that only good things b=\r\nefall my body, my name, my family\netc [because I really care about them and=\r\n any damage to them will upset\nme]&quot; has missed the point big time! The subl=\r\nime verse you referred to is\nlike the culmination of entire Bhagavad Gita a=\r\nnd is the essence of all\nUpanishads.\n&gt; =C2\n&gt; *=C2 =C2 =C2 =C2 =C2 =C2 =C2  =\r\n*=C2 =C2 =C2 =C2 =C2 =C2\n=C2  *\n&gt; =C2\n&gt; One word of caution. IMHO, what fol=\r\nlows is far more relevant to most\nreaders of this writeup than what lies ab=\r\nove!\n&gt; =C2\n&gt; This verse is the essence of Self-knowledge. But most people o=\r\nf this\nera are unlikely to realize Self (until the end of this yuga cycle).=\r\n So\nmy suggestion is to set more reasonable goals. It is ok if you haven&#39;t\n=\r\nsurrendered all of your dharmas to Lord.\n&gt; =C2\n&gt; !!!!! In fact, even if you=\r\n try, you will probably end up misusing that\nnotion to run away from most o=\r\nf your higher (and selfless) dharmas and\nyet end up sticking to your lowest=\r\n and most selfish dharmas (e.g. dharma\ntowards body and its survival instin=\r\nct, very tough to shake off). That\nis useless. !!!!!\n&gt; =C2\n&gt; No wonder Veda=\r\nnta comes at the end of all Veda and the verse above\ncomes after so many ch=\r\napters on so many other things. Don&#39;t jump to it\nright away!\n&gt; =C2\n&gt; First =\r\n*expand* your sense of self and your sense of responsibility and\nattachment=\r\n to be more inclusive. Current body-mind co